        <name>16.1.1.5 Find the nth term of a sequence</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Verify that the following sequence is convergent.\[\dfrac{3}{1\times 2}, \dfrac{4}{2\times 3}, \dfrac{5}{3\times 4}, \ldots\]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;First, find the expression for the \(n^{th}\) term:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\(a_n =\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Now, find the limit of \(a_n\) as \(n\) increases:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\(\displaystyle \lim_{n\to \infty} a_n = \) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;The \(n^{th}\) term of the sequence is given by \[\displaystyle a_n = {@ta1@}.\]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;(Note that by substituting&amp;nbsp;\(n=1\) in the expression&amp;nbsp;above, we obtain \(a_1 = \dfrac{3}{1\times 2}\) for the first term, as required. Similarly, for the second and third terms.)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Then, as \(n\) increases, \[{@ta1@} = \left[ \dfrac{1+\dfrac{2}{n}}{n+1} \right] \to \dfrac{1}{n+1} \to {@ta2@}.\]Hence, \(\displaystyle \lim_{n\to \infty} a_n = {@ta2@}\). Thus, the series is convergent, since this limit can be found.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</generalfeedback>
